image.altText: Noel holds up an Indigenous clap stick at the National Press Club speakers podium.

props.synopsis: Noel Pearson, an Indigenous Australian lawyer and land rights activist, addresses the National Press Club. Follow live.

title.children: Noel Pearson argues Yes vote will 'complete Australia', says it's vital referendum succeed

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: "Not one square inch of land was lost because of Mabo. "Not one square inch of land was lost because of Wick. "All of these scare campaigns that have looped around and revisited this referendum campaign are just saying the things that never happened. "Nobody lost any land. The High Court's genius in native title was to balance the rights of the Indigenous peoples with the rights of the new Australians. And we got the balance right. "Now we have the Australian peoples' chance to get it right in relation to the constitution, and what we are going to vote on on October 14 is the perfect balance."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Final question: What is your pitch to the undecided voter?

children.content: "Not one square inch of land was lost because of Mabo.
"Not one square inch of land was lost because of Wick.
"All of these scare campaigns that have looped around and revisited this referendum campaign are just saying the things that never happened.
"Nobody lost any land. The High Court's genius in native title was to balance the rights of the Indigenous peoples with the rights of the new Australians. And we got the balance right.
"Now we have the Australian peoples' chance to get it right in relation to the constitution, and what we are going to vote on on October 14 is the perfect balance."

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: ABC News reporter Nicole Hegarty has asked if the Yes campaign will be able to sell its message in the face of the No campaign strategy. Pearson: "This really is a test of whether our democracy can sustain a discourse for good. "Can we do good things in our democracy by talking to one another? "In a situation where bots and robo calls and the sheer filth in the sewers of the Internet come into play — can we still do good things in the democracy through putting our case to other citizens in our country? "And appealing to the intelligence and their hearts? Can we do good things? Can we rise to the occasion given the new circumstances we're in? It's going to be a test."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: A test of discourse in democracy

children.content: ABC News reporter Nicole Hegarty has asked if the Yes campaign will be able to sell its message in the face of the No campaign strategy.
Pearson: "This really is a test of whether our democracy can sustain a discourse for good.
"Can we do good things in our democracy by talking to one another?

"In a situation where bots and robo calls and the sheer filth in the sewers of the Internet come into play — can we still do good things in the democracy through putting our case to other citizens in our country?
"And appealing to the intelligence and their hearts? Can we do good things? Can we rise to the occasion given the new circumstances we're in? It's going to be a test."

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Here are the final lines of Noel Pearson's speech: "On October 14, we whisper into the wind of time that 'No gets us nowhere and Yes makes it possible'. "On October 14, we can carve our generation's name into the bedrock of history. "And for as long as there is history in this land, it will be recorded — we were asked and we proudly voted Yes. We can do this for the love of our country. The love of Australia. My land. Your land. Our land."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Noel Pearson recieves a standing ovation

children.content: Here are the final lines of Noel Pearson's speech:
"On October 14, we whisper into the wind of time that 'No gets us nowhere and Yes makes it possible'.
"On October 14, we can carve our generation's name into the bedrock of history.

"And for as long as there is history in this land, it will be recorded — we were asked and we proudly voted Yes. We can do this for the love of our country. The love of Australia. My land. Your land. Our land."

image.altText: A composite image of Ben Carroll and Jacinta Allan.

props.synopsis: Deputy Premier Jacinta Allan may be facing a challenge from Public Transport Minister Ben Carroll in her bid to replace Daniel Andrews after his shock resignation on Tuesday.  Follow all the action in our live blog.

title.children: Showdown looms for Victoria's top job as Labor MPs meet

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Since yesterday, Jacinta Allan has been the frontrunner to replace Daniel Andrews. But this just in from state political reporter Bridget Rollason: We're hearing Deputy Premier Jacinta Allan could face a challenge for the Labor party leadership. Labor MPs have told the ABC Public Transport Minister Ben Carroll could put his hat in the ring for the top job, meaning it might be a showdown between Ms Allan and Mr Carroll. The caucus meeting to choose the new leader is set to get underway shortly — ministers are waiting for outgoing premier Daniel Andrews to arrive.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Signs it may not be 'smooth sailing' for Jacinta Allan

children.content: Since yesterday, Jacinta Allan has been the frontrunner to replace Daniel Andrews.
But this just in from state political reporter Bridget Rollason:
We're hearing Deputy Premier Jacinta Allan could face a challenge for the Labor party leadership.
Labor MPs have told the ABC Public Transport Minister Ben Carroll could put his hat in the ring for the top job, meaning it might be a showdown between Ms Allan and Mr Carroll.
The caucus meeting to choose the new leader is set to get underway shortly — ministers are waiting for outgoing premier Daniel Andrews to arrive.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: This just in from state political reporter Bridget Rollason: It's looking like Treasurer Tim Pallas could be Victoria's next Deputy Labor Leader. Labor sources say Mental Health Minister Gab Williams threw her hat in the ring but has withdrawn, with the left likely to support Mr Pallas, as factional meetings continue. Public Transport Minister Ben Carroll may still nominate for the position from the right faction.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Tim Pallas appears to be ahead in race for deputy leader

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: More from state political reporter Bridget Rollason, who's down at Parliament House: Arriving at parliament, the Victorian treasurer says the outcome of the new leader is "entirely in the hands of the caucus" but hasn't ruled out a tilt at deputy. "People have been writing me off for many years now," Mr Pallas says. "I haven't made a decision about my future other than I want to serve Labor for as long as I possibly can."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Tim Pallas won't rule out running for deputy leadership
